element_texts.text: 1862 The severity of the winter the high floods and deep snows had financially ruined a large class of our population, and a tremendous mining excitement springing up in the Salmon River Country; up Snake Run in Washington Territory. and in consequence thereof a large portion of the laboring population drifted off in that direction in hopes to make up their losses by a streak of good fortune in the mines. Like most gold excitements this proved to be a humbug to a great extent. Yet extensive & rich mines new opened. Cities & towns built up. and a dense mining population crowded in & filled up the country drained by the Columbia River and even penetrated the Region by the summit of the Rocky Mountains. Prospecting the Rivers & their tributaries for gold, searching for choice valley for farming, locating sites for towns, and daily contending with the hostile Indians always to be found in way to check & harass and impede & annoy the pioneer advance of civilization. I had contemplated going in that direction myself and try & make up my

losses, but was prevailed upon by friends to stay and be a candidate for Co. Clerk & was triumphantly elected when the election day came round and I soon entered upon the duties of the office. The labor light, pay good, and the great objection being that it required a person to be on hand at all times during business hours, hence very confining to one who is as fond of outdoor life as I am; The summer gradually wore away, and winter was upon us, mild & wet. The Legislature which meet in Sept disorganized Umpqua County & attached it to Douglas and thus all the Umpqua Valley is now embraced in Douglas as the act took efect in July 1863, and it became my duty to remove the County property to Roseburg the County seat of Douglas County and surrender it up with proper authorities which was done on the 5 of the month, and by the act of the Legislature aforesaid I was thus Legislated out of a portion of the term for which I had been elected. A.W.S. Land office being at Roseburg, I hired out and

found to leave the River and lead up a spur of the mountain to the left, thence along a ridge for about 2 miles when we descended to a stream about 6 feet wide flowing into the South Umpqua a short distance to the right of us  Crossing this little stream the trail led directly up the spur of a mountain on the opposite side and on an along a high ridge for about 5 1/2 miles to the head of a small spring branch on the right of the trail.  its waters running off to the right or southerl?y to the No. Umpqua.  It had been represented to us that good grass could be obtained at this place, and we were disappointed in not being able to find any at all.  however we were obliged to camp for the night but our horses fared poorly.  A little Pea vine growing in the heavy timber was all the feed the animals could obtain
Saturday Sept 19 1863
Our cours?e was Easterly on the trail which followed a high winding Ridge which soon became rocky boulders and broken Basalt thickly scattered over the surface, with deep canyons on each side.  after travelling about 11 miles, we found

up stream, crossing several small ? and we were obliged to camp for the night without grass for the horses  The mountains are high and rocky & very heavily timbered. the travel to the mines above has as a general thing been confined to the old Indian trails. that lead over the high ridges, where to say the least very poor trails have been made, to their fisheries on some stream, thence to their hunting grounds in the mountains, then to their fisheries again or to more distant hunting grounds in the far off interior  Saw a few deer but found them to be very wild.  killed several grouse, but failed to get any shots at larger game
Sunday Sept 20 1863
About 3 miles this morning brought us to a stream coming in from N.W. and about 10 feet wide, and a little grass growing in bunches along the margins.  we concluded to camp and give our horses the benefit of what little there might be found in the vicinity  It rained and was quite unpleasant in the P. M.  Crayfish a species of small red lobster abounds in all the streams and a large quantity of them were caught and boiled in a Camp kettle

that the ridge which we had been following came to an abrupt termination, and that the trail wound its way down over broken rocks to the North fork of the North Umpqua River, and we soon found ourselves on the bank below.  This stream unites with the main stream a short distance below, and from the spur just before we began the descent we could see the main Canyon of the North Umpqua for a distance of 15 or 20 miles up Stream in a course about S. E.  Both streams appear to run through deep canyons, and are filled with rapids & cascades. The N. Fork of the N. Umpqua is a stream of about 50 feet wide and flows over a rocky bed, and upon the stream a few miles above is where the limited amount of mining has been done.  Our trail led us up this Stream in the left side about one mile to a perpendicular fall of 8 feet, where the stream falls over a solid formation of red granite. About 3 miles further

miners -- It appears to be more plenty upon the bars or on and near the surface in the loose sand  A few quartz boulders are found upon the stream, but Basalt predominates, with scattering granite  A little feed for animals was to be found scattering through the timber and we turned them out and put up for the day and were kindly and hospitably entertained by the miners
Tuesday Sept 22 1863
Did not leave this camp today  The country having been thoroughly explored and prospected from the settlements on the River below to this point.  and the prevailing opinion of all who have any knowledge of this part of the Cascade Range, is that the main Summit between the waters of the N?. Umpqua River and the Willamette River, is a high divide running Easterly from this locality, in a direct course to the main summit of the Cascades, and that said summit could be reached from here in about one day, hence the proposition to explore the Country with? Eastward from this particular point to the Des Chutes River and the Dalles and California trail on the opposite or east side.  This

and eaten with a keen relish. It was amusing to see the men wade in the water to catch those animals.  Hamblin & Davenport were for two or three hours in the water too? and sometimes as deep as 3 feet armed with sticks in search among the rocks for their game.  water cold, and men wet from head to foot.  Boiled lobsters were heartily eaten by all but was a new dish for all except myself
Monday Set 21 1863
Had an early start.  trail rough and at one and one half miles came to another 8 feet perpendicular fall over a ledge of gray granite, and at about 5 miles further the stream divides into two forks or prongs of nearly the same width.  We followed the trail which led us up the left hand fork and at about one quarter of a mile further we came to the miners cabins where we found John Easton, Ths Shrum, George Kerns James Fordyce and D. L Watson engaged in gold mining.  and by hard work it was found that they were making about $3 per day.  the gold being very fine and is termed "drift" gold by

from others as well as my own personal knowledge of the Country beyond:  I soon made up my mind that the main Summit of the Cascade Range must be much farther to the Eastman than the miners in this vicinity generally believes. The prevailing opinion among the miners was that we could reach the summit by a direct? ridge in one day.  and from my own knowledge of the Country beyond I was satisfied that we could reach the trail where our expedition would terminate.  from the summit in one day without great effort. and thus the general opinion was at once fixed that we could reach the trail in two days and return in two more.  Thus Consuming four days from this Camp to the trail and back  Notwithstanding the miners all appeared to believe that the trip could be made in 4 days.  yet they recommended that we take 5 days provisions.  but making an estimate of what I believed the distance to be I found it necessary to start with breadstuffs enough to last us 16 days:  So our preperations were soon began for an early start tomorrow morning. The mountains being so rough and rocky and so destitute

information was found to ? the firm opinion of all who claimed to have any knowledge of the Country, and as there was no variety of opinion, nor regard to the summit ridge and main divide, therefore reliance was placed in the correctness of the opinion:  But after all agreeing upon the favorable route I was not quite prepared to believe that the main summit of the Cascade Range of mountains, was quite so near to us. and my opinion was based upon a former knowledge obtained while travelling along the East side of said Range in 1860 during which time I acquired a very correct idea of all the Snowy peaks and other noted Land marks.  always to be seen along and near the summit of the mountains:  During that year {1860) I learned the fact that the main summit of the Range is generally from 4 to 10 miles from the Eastern base, and that from the foot of the mountains on the East side it is not over 15 miles to the Dalles & California trail where we expect to terminate our expedition.  After considering all the information I could obtain

upon the opposite side, and steered in an easterly Course as near as the general character of the Country would permit.  A little afternoon we found a deep canyon before us which it became necessary to cross  At the bottom we found a rapid little stream of 6 feet wide flowing south.  After crossing the Canyon we had very nice travelling for a few miles and went into Camp quite early on  a small branch were we happened to kill a deer which added to the luxuries of camp life  Davenport has been unwell for two or three days, and is worse today.  is badly afflicted with bloody flux, Country rough today.  Saw many quartz boulders scattered promiscuously over the highlands.  also other indications of minerals and also Copper Sulphpherets
Thursday Sept 24 1863
Davenport is much worse today. is not in a condition to travel but he was in favor of trying it rather than delay the expedition.  About 1/4 mile brought us to a rapid little stream of ten feet wide running south where much crystalized Quartz rock is to be found.  We cross this stream and ascend a high and

of grass, that our horses had suffered from the want of feed, and the country with Eastman being of a similar character of worse, we decided to send our animals back to the settlement by a couple of the miners who were about to return. The animals had been a great hindrance so far and the men highly pleased with the prospect of being relieved from them and were more than willing to pack their blankets and grub on their backs:  Our Outfit selected was a small tent, one blanket for each person, three guns, a camp axe, and frying pan & a couple of tin cups. Our horses were sent below and everything was in readiness for an early Start into a rough mountainous region never before explored
Wednesday Sept 23 1863
D. L. Watson started out with us, thus making a Company of five, a nice and convivial little Company for mountaineering  Our packs were put up and bidding good by to the hospitable miners we set out.  we crossed the creek a little below the camp and ascended the mountain

A short distance through heavy timber this morning and we came to quite a high bold ridge which it became necessary to cross. and from the summit of which we had one of those magnifficent mountain views so common to the Oregon Mountaineers.  Diamond Peak a high Snowy Mountain. lay N. W of us and is situated on the Summit ridge at the N. side of the head of the middle fork of the Willamette River, and another snowy Butte lying S. E. and near the head of the Umpqua River and Rogue River  also several other peaks and rocky craters and cones along the summit which I readily recognized, which proved at once that I was much nearerunderlined correct in my estimates than the miners.  From these developements it was  certain we would not reach the summit for several days  A rock chimny or crater directly to the east of us and plainly visible from the trail beyond the mountains will be our guide for the present  Decending on the east side down into a deep timbered canyon to a stream about 8 feet wide running N. to the Willamette River and camped under a thick grove of large

steep mountain on the opposite side, finding high bush huckleberries common to the mountainous regions. in Great profusion and very ripe and delicious.  Much time was lost in picking berries, and while thus delayed we killed several grouse.  On the top of this mountain and on the eastern slope we found some open land, and descending on the opposite side to a spended little prarie of 40 or 50 acres through which we discovered an Indian trail. quite plain running in a course of N. W. & S. E., this trail did not exactly lead in the direction we desired to go, but followed it a mile or two and found it making too much Southing we left to our right and crossing a few small spring branches we camped for the night having travelled about 6 miles.  Davenport being too sick to travel further.
Friday Sept 25 1863
Davenport is no better, but is in good spirits and proposes to make a short distance today being strongly impressed with the belief that he will be better tomorrow:

I suppose we was downstream about 2 miles and found it to be but one Continuous rapid and cascades all the way.  its General Course about due south.  Granite, Basalt, Conglomerate, Sand Rock, Quarts, and spar was every where visible.  the day was a dark and dismal one.  rained at intervals all day. At a point about one mile be low Camp, where the stream run through a gorge with perpendicular rock on one side, and a sloping rock, steep at an angle of a little more than 45o on the opposite side:  we found it impassible to pass this place.  only by creeping along the sloping rock on the left at a point about one hundred feet above the stream which looked practicable.  However before we had quite passed the rock it was found to be more dangerous than we had at first considered.  Being somewhat in advance of Hamlin, and walking carefully, with my gun in my right hand and clinging to the rock wherever I could find any place to cling to, and the blades of grass which occasionally appear.  for it was

hemlocks. Davenport being? much more than in the morning  We saw several deer today and killed one. Davenports case has assumed a serious and dangerous character.  We did not make over 3 miles to day.  we had a very nice camping ground, but was rendered unpleasant by heavy rain in the P.M.
Saturday Sept 26 1863
Last night was stormy and blustering.  rained in torrents all night.  Davenport worse; and we commenced restricting him to a light diet and administering copious drafts of hemlock tea  We found it impracticable to move to day and therefore lay in Camp. This morning Mr Watson, finding their opinions as to the Summit of the mountains, to be so far from the facts, concluded to return to the mining camp.  We could not prevail upon him to continue with us.  we were sorry to part with him.  he left early on his return  Hamlin and myself explored the stream for some distance below. and Jones remained to take care of Davenport

certain that a false step of any kind would send a fellow to the bottom, which might be a dangerous face:  The rock was wet and wherever the dirt appeared upon its surface was exceeding slippery:  and before I had passed to a place of safety, my finger hold gave way and I fell and at once found myself on my back head downwards and sliding down the rock towards the stream below at a frightful rate.  I expected to have my brains dashed out on the boulders below, but happened to strike the stream where the water was about 3 feet deep & no boulders for about ten steps? above or below.  I was bruised up considerable but not hurt seriously:  My gun was found in the stream at full cock with the cap gone 
Sunday Sept 27 1863
Large quantities of rain fell during the night.  Davenport was more comfortable than he had been for a day or two.  was very weak, but was in favor of starting and going a short distance  Everything was very wet, but it did not rain as we set out but commenced very soon afterwards

Monday Sept 28 1863
A more unpleasant night was seldom ever passed by mountaineers or another class of people.  the wind roared through the gorges and canyons and over the ridges the atmosphere was soon too cold for rain, hence the falling elements was changed into snow  It was with much differently that we managed to keep our fire burning during the night  Davenport was so badly exposed that I feared the Consequence.  this morning the snow was about 4 inches deep, and still falling.  A prudent man would move camp in such a storm unless in case of extreme emergency  We therefore considered to day over for the day and make ourselves as comfortable as the State of the weather would permit.  The storm continued until about 3. P.M. when it subsided and a thick fog eveloped the whole country.  At Sundown the fog partially cleared away.  the snow nearly a foot deep.  Game appears plenty in this vicinity.  many deer tracks were seen in the snow near camp and several grouse were killed

and although we were having an unpleasant time, yet were living well
Sept 29}. Davenport appears much better this morning, so much so that we now believe him in a fair way to recover  Last night was cold and ice froze in the pools of water near camp so that no water could be had except snow water.  the sun rose bright with a clear sky overhead. We set out in an easterly course and upon  the summit of the Ridge about 1/4 mile from camp we found the snow considerable deeper.  from this point descend down into another deep canyon to a rapid rocky stream of 15 feet wide running North into Wilamette  Crossing this stream and ascending the mountain on the opposite side for about 2 miles when we reach another Summit running W.? & S. with a canyon East of us.  The snow on this Summit is over a foot deep and and the thick evergreen timber appears in places to be completeley roofed over:  following this ridge southerly for about a half mile we ascended a rocky emminence where we had a fine view of the surroun-
